{"title": "Words Worth a Thousand Pictures: Measuring and Understanding Perceptual Variability in Text-to-Image Generation", "abstract": "Diffusion models are the state of the art in text-to-image generation, but their perceptual variability remains understudied. In this paper, we examine how prompts affect image variability in black-box diffusion-based models. We propose W1KP, a human-calibrated measure of variability in a set of images, bootstrapped from existing image-pair perceptual distances. Current datasets do not cover recent diffusion models, thus we curate three test sets for evaluation. Our best perceptual distance outperforms nine baselines by up to 18 points in accuracy, and our calibration matches graded human judgements 78% of the time. Using W1KP, we study prompt reusability and show that Imagen prompts can be reused for 10-50 random seeds before new images become too similar to already generated images, while Stable Diffusion XL and DALL-E 3 can be reused 50-200 times. Lastly, we analyze 56 linguistic features of real prompts, finding that the prompt’s length, CLIP embedding norm, concreteness, and word senses influence variability most. As far as we are aware, we are the first to analyze diffusion variability from a visuolinguistic perspective. Our project page is at http://w1kp.com.", "doi": "10.18653/v1/2024.emnlp-main.311", "url": "https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.311.pdf", "extracted": true, "datafile": "2024.emnlp.xml", "authors": [{"first": "Raphael", "last": "Tang"}, {"first": "Crystina", "last": "Zhang"}, {"first": "Lixinyu", "last": "Xu"}, {"first": "Yao", "last": "Lu"}, {"first": "Wenyan", "last": "Li"}, {"first": "Pontus", "last": "Stenetorp"}, {"first": "Jimmy", "last": "Lin"}, {"first": "Ferhan", "last": "Ture"}], "question": "લેખકોએ કયા proprietary અને open-source modelsને લક્ષિત કર્યા હતા?", "model_id": "GenVRadmin/AryaBhatta-GemmaUltra-Merged", "model_config": "k50_p0.90_t0.1", "lang": "gujarati", "prompt": "Tang,Raphael  et al. દ્વારા \"Words Worth a Thousand Pictures: Measuring and Understanding Perceptual Variability in Text-to-Image Generation\" શીર્ષકવાળા લેખમાં, લેખકોએ કયા proprietary અને open-source modelsને લક્ષિત કર્યા હતા? અહીં લેખના સારાંશનો એક ભાગ છે, જે તમે સંદર્ભ તરીકે ઉપયોગ કરી શકો છો: Diffusion models are the state of the art in text-to-image generation, but their perceptual variability remains understudied. In this paper, we examine how prompts affect image variability in black-box diffusion-based models. We propose W1KP, a human-calibrated measure of variability in a set of images, bootstrapped from existing image-pair perceptual distances. Current datasets do not cover recent diffusion models, thus we cur", "output_text": "ated a new dataset, Diffusion-1k, containing 1000 prompts and corresponding images for 12 models. We find that the variability of the models is highly correlated with their performance on standard metrics, such as FID. We also show that the variability of the models is highly correlated with their performance on human-calibrated metrics, such as W1KP, demonstrating the effectiveness of our new metric. Finally, we show that the variability of the models is highly correlated with their performance on a new metric, called Human-10, which measures the similarity between the images generated by the model and the prompt.### Input:### Response:The article \"Words Worth a Thousand Pictures: Measuring and Understanding Perceptual Variability in Text-to-Image Generation\" by Tang, Raphael et al. discusses the effectiveness of proprietary and open-source models in text-to-image generation. The authors examine how prompts affect image variability in black-box diffusion-based models and propose a new metric called W1KP to measure variability in a set of images. They also curate a new dataset, Diffusion-1k, containing 1000 prompts and corresponding images for 12 models. The article finds that the variability of the models is highly correlated with their performance on standard metrics, such as FID, and human-calibrated metrics, such as W1KP. Finally, the article shows that the variability of the models is highly correlated with their performance on a new metric called Human-10, which measures the similarity between the images generated by the model and the prompt.", "output_tokens": ["\n", "ated", "▁a", "▁new", "▁dataset", ",", "▁Diffusion", "-", "1", "k", ",", "▁containing", "▁", "1", "0", "0", "0", "▁prompts", "▁and", "▁corresponding", "▁images", "▁for", "▁", "1", "2", "▁models", ".", "▁We", "▁find", "▁that", "▁the", "▁variability", "▁of", "▁the", "▁models", "▁is", "▁highly", "▁correlated", "▁with", "▁their", "▁performance", "▁on", "▁standard", "▁metrics", ",", "▁such", "▁as", "▁FID", ".", "▁We", "▁also", "▁show", "▁that", "▁the", "▁variability", "▁of", "▁the", "▁models", "▁is", "▁highly", "▁correlated", "▁with", "▁their", "▁performance", "▁on", "▁human", "-", "cal", "ibrated", "▁metrics", ",", "▁such", "▁as", "▁W", "1", "KP", ",", "▁demonstrating", "▁the", "▁effectiveness", "▁of", "▁our", "▁new", "▁metric", ".", "▁Finally", ",", "▁we", "▁show", "▁that", "▁the", "▁variability", "▁of", "▁the", "▁models", "▁is", "▁highly", "▁correlated", "▁with", "▁their", "▁performance", "▁on", "▁a", "▁new", "▁metric", ",", "▁called", "▁Human", "-", "1", "0", ",", "▁which", "▁measures", "▁the", "▁similarity", "▁between", "▁the", "▁images", "▁generated", "▁by", "▁the", "▁model", "▁and", "▁the", "▁prompt", ".", "\n\n", "###", "▁Input", ":", "\n\n\n", "###", "▁Response", ":", "\n", "The", "▁article", "▁\"", "Words", "▁Worth", "▁a", "▁Thousand", "▁Pictures", ":", "▁Measuring", "▁and", "▁Understanding", "▁Per", "ceptual", "▁Variability", "▁in", "▁Text", "-", "to", "-", "Image", "▁Generation", "\"", "▁by", "▁Tang", ",", "▁Raphael", "▁et", "▁al", ".", "▁discusses", "▁the", "▁effectiveness", "▁of", "▁proprietary", "▁and", "▁open", "-", "source", "▁models", "▁in", "▁text", "-", "to", "-", "image", "▁generation", ".", "▁The", "▁authors", "▁examine"